<UL>
  <LI>[&nbsp;<a
  href="http://babbage.cs.qc.edu/courses/cs341/IEEE-754.html">Decimal to
  IEEE-754 Floating-Point</a>&nbsp;]

  <LI>[&nbsp;<a
  href="http://babbage.cs.qc.edu/courses/cs341/IEEE-754hex32.html">
  32-bit IEEE-754 Floating-Point to Decimal.</a>&nbsp;]

  <LI>[&nbsp;<a
  href="http://babbage.cs.qc.edu/courses/cs341/IEEE-754hex64.html">
  64-bit IEEE-754 Floating-Point to Decimal</a>&nbsp;]

  <LI>[&nbsp;<a
  href="http://babbage.cs.qc.edu/courses/cs341/IEEE-754references.html">Reference
  material on the IEEE-754 Floating-Point Standard</a>&nbsp;]

</UL>

The first web page was originally developed by a Queens College student,
Quanfei Wen, and subsequently modified and extended by Kevin Brewer of
Delco Electronics.  Kevin also wrote the other three pages listed.<p>

The web pages use JavaScript programs to do the arithmetic operations,
and Kevin has added a lot of comments describing the IEEE-754 formats to
the code.  You can use your browser's "View->Page Source" menu choices
(or equivalent) to look at the JavaScript code and comments.<p>

Many thanks to Fei for the original page, and to Kevin for all the work
he put into them, and for making his work available to us.

